<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  ============================================================================
  XBRL Taxonomy Package : META-INF/catalog.xml
  ============================================================================

  Vendor-neutral skeleton. Replace the example URIs and paths with the actual
  authoritative HTTP(S) namespaces and the corresponding folders inside this
  package zip.

  WHAT IS THIS FILE?

  An OASIS XML Catalog (XML Catalogs 1.1, OASIS Standard, 7 October 2005).
  An XML Catalog tells a processor: "if you are about to fetch this remote
  URI, use this local file instead." Inside an XBRL Taxonomy Package this
  lets validators (Arelle, ESEF Filing Manager, regulator tooling, etc.)
  resolve every schemaRef / linkbaseRef / xs:import / xs:include reference
  to a file inside the package, with NO internet access required.

  WHY DOES IT MATTER?

    * Reproducibility. Auditors validating the same filing five years from
      now must get bit-identical results, even after the publisher's server
      is gone or the URL has rotted.
    * Offline / air-gapped validation. Banks, regulators, and audit firms
      routinely run XBRL processors on isolated networks.
    * Performance. Avoids hundreds of HTTPS round-trips to taxonomy hosts.
    * Determinism. Guarantees the processor uses the exact taxonomy version
      bundled in the package, not whatever is currently published online.

  WHERE MUST IT LIVE?

  Inside the package zip, at exactly:

      <top-level-dir>/META-INF/catalog.xml

  per Taxonomy Packages 1.0 (REC-2016-04-19) sections 3.2 and 3.3. The file
  is OPTIONAL, but if present it MUST be a valid XML Catalog AND MUST
  conform to the restricted schema in Appendix B.2 of that spec, otherwise
  the package fails with error tpe:invalidCatalogFile.

  PATH RESOLUTION

  Relative URIs in @rewritePrefix are resolved relative to THIS file's
  location. Since this file lives in META-INF/, a leading "../" is needed
  to reach the package root. (XML Base may be used to change this; see
  Taxonomy Packages 1.0 section 3.3.)

  WHICH CATALOG DIRECTIVES ARE ALLOWED IN AN XBRL TAXONOMY PACKAGE?

  Taxonomy Packages 1.0 defines a *restricted subset* of OASIS XML Catalogs
  1.1 (see Appendix B.2, taxonomy-package-catalog.xsd). The catalog element
  may contain ONLY:

      ALLOWED:
        <rewriteURI uriStartString="..." rewritePrefix="..."/>
        (plus elements/attributes from foreign namespaces, treated as
         extensions and ignored by conformant XBRL processors)

      DISALLOWED in an XBRL Taxonomy Package catalog:
        <rewriteSystem>            (the system-ID variant)
        <public>, <system>         (PUBLIC / SYSTEM identifier mappings)
        <uri>                      (single-URI mapping)
        <delegatePublic>, <delegateSystem>, <delegateURI>
        <nextCatalog>
        <group>
        Two <rewriteURI> entries with the same @uriStartString
            (additional XBRL restriction, error
             tpe:multipleRewriteURIsForStartString)

  WHY ONLY rewriteURI (AND NOT rewriteSystem)?

  In OASIS XML Catalogs 1.1 the two directives serve different lookups:

    * rewriteSystem  (attributes: systemIdStartString, rewritePrefix)
        Matches against an XML *system identifier*, typically used by
        SAX/DOM parsers when resolving DOCTYPE / SYSTEM declarations and
        xsi:schemaLocation hints.

    * rewriteURI     (attributes: uriStartString, rewritePrefix)
        Matches against any URI submitted to the catalog resolver,
        including the URIs used by xs:import / xs:include schemaLocation,
        XBRL link:schemaRef and link:linkbaseRef xlink:href values, and
        XLink href values inside linkbases.

  XBRL processors resolve every reference (schemaRef, linkbaseRef,
  xs:import, xs:include, XLink href) through the URI resolution path, so
  rewriteURI is sufficient AND is the only directive the Taxonomy Packages
  1.0 schema permits. Adding <rewriteSystem> here would be schema-invalid
  and the package would be rejected with tpe:invalidCatalogFile.

  ATTRIBUTE NAMES (verified against Taxonomy Packages 1.0, Appendix B.2)

    rewriteURI:
      @uriStartString  REQUIRED. Prefix to match against the URI being
                       resolved. Longest match wins when multiple
                       rewriteURI entries share a common prefix.
      @rewritePrefix   REQUIRED. Replacement prefix (typically a relative
                       path that starts with "../" because this file lives
                       in META-INF/).

  REFERENCES

    [XML Catalogs 1.1] OASIS Standard, 7 October 2005.
    [Taxonomy Packages 1.0] XBRL International, REC-2016-04-19,
        especially section 3.3 "The catalog.xml file" and Appendix B.2
        "taxonomy-package-catalog.xsd".
  ============================================================================
-->
<catalog xmlns="urn:oasis:names:tc:entity:xmlns:xml:catalog">

  <!-- Catalog rewrites apply to ABSOLUTE URIs that authoritative entry points carry.
       The bundled scaffold uses RELATIVE hrefs in taxonomyPackage.xml's entryPointDocument,
       which bypass catalog rewriting by design. Real filings typically use absolute
       namespace URIs (e.g. http://www.your-org.com/taxonomy/2024/...) here so the catalog
       can rewrite them to the bundled file at validation time. -->

  <!--
    Primary remapping for the example taxonomy.

    A processor that needs to resolve, e.g.:
        http://example.com/taxonomy/example/2025-01-01/example.xsd
    will rewrite the prefix and load:
        ../example/2025-01-01/example.xsd
    (resolved relative to META-INF/, i.e.
     <pkg-root>/example/2025-01-01/example.xsd).

    Replace `http://example.com/taxonomy/example/` with the canonical
    HTTP(S) namespace of your taxonomy entry point, and replace
    `../example/` with the corresponding folder inside the package.
  -->
  <rewriteURI
      uriStartString="http://example.com/taxonomy/example/"
      rewritePrefix="../example/"/>

  <!--
    Optional second remapping for a nested or related taxonomy module
    bundled in the same package (for example, a country-specific
    extension or a separately versioned linkbase set).

    Demonstrates that multiple rewriteURI entries are allowed; each must
    have a UNIQUE @uriStartString (post URI-normalization), otherwise the
    package fails with tpe:multipleRewriteURIsForStartString.
  -->
  <rewriteURI
      uriStartString="http://example.com/taxonomy/example-extension/"
      rewritePrefix="../example-extension/"/>

</catalog>
